<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 94 / Finance and the Family: International Bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors in international bond funds have enjoyed high returns, writes
Scheherazade Daneshkhu. As the table shows, the average fund returned 57 per
cent over the three years to January 1 (offer-to-bid with net income
re-invested).
This strong performance has resulted from a particularly favourable
combination of factors. The devaluation of sterling after it left the
exchange rate mechanism in September 1992 was the main cause but substantial
falls in inflation and in short-term interest rates also have helped.
Investors cannot necessarily expect the same degree of performance in the
future, though, as the same combination of factors might not recur. But
Jeremy Cunningham, manager of the Invesco International Bond fund, believes
there is more growth to come because European interest rates will fall
'quite considerably' this year. Some 80 per cent of this fund is placed in
European fixed-interest investments.
At the top of the table, the Norwich International Bond trust returned 72.5
per cent over the period to its investors and has an above-average yield of
5.1 per cent. But performance has slipped in the year to January 1 with the
fund's ranking falling to 20 of 27, according to Micropal.
Brian Dowler, a fund manager at NU Investment Management, says 1991 was a
very good year for the fund but believes it could have been underweight in
Japanese bonds at certain periods last year, so missing out on the
significant appreciation of the yen in 1993.
Charges on the Norwich fund are 6 per cent initial and 1.25 per cent annual.
The Invesco fund has an 1.05 per cent initial charge and an annual fee of
0.5 per cent.
