<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow hits fresh high on
inflation cheer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A tame reading on fourth-quarter inflation pushed US stocks further into
uncharted territory yesterday, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 19.13 ahead at 3,945.43, well
above the short-lived record of 3,926.30 set the previous session. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 improved 1.65 at 478.70. In secondary
markets, the American SE composite was 1.36 better at 483.22, and the Nasdaq
composite added 3.65 to 796.53.
NYSE activity was heavy, with 314m shares exchanged. Advances led declines,
1,300 to 756.
After a surprising rally in bond prices the previous session, stocks were
poised for their fourth record-breaking Friday in a row. Investors were not
disappointed, as the Dow blue-chip barometer opened more than 25 points
higher after the Commerce Department released its initial estimate for gross
domestic product in the final three months of 1993.
The data were better than expected on two counts. First, the economy
expanded by a robust 5.9 per cent, higher than the consensus forecast of 5.2
per cent but not entirely surprising given recent statements by senior
government officials. The most welcome news concerned inflation, with the
price deflator inching up only 1.3 per cent, well below expectations of 2.5
per cent.
In reaction, the long end of the US Treasury market, which is especially
vulnerable to inflationary pressures, registered fresh gains. By midday, the
benchmark 30-year note was up  21/32 to 100 1/2, and the yield dropped to
6.208 per cent.
The prospect of lower interest rates helped bank issues in general. Bankers
Trust, up Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 82 1/4, and JP Morgan, Dollars 3/4 ahead
at Dollars 71 1/8, received an extra boost from SG Warburg, which upgraded
the stocks.
But it was Continental Bank that stood out from the rest of the sector. It
jumped Dollars 6 1/2 to Dollars 34 1/2 after the announcement of its
acquisition by BankAmerica for Dollars 1.9bn in cash and stock. BankAmerica,
which said it would buy back Dollars 500m in its shares before completing
the deal, dipped Dollars 3/8 to Dollars 45 3/8.
The agreement lifted some regional banks, which are potential takeover
targets. Wells Fargo climbed Dollars 3 7/8 to Dollars 138 7/8 and First
Interstate Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 71 1/2.
The week's stream of corporate earnings news slowed to a trickle yesterday.
One of those reporting was Scientific-Atlanta, a supplier of satellite,
cable television and data transmission equipment. It plunged Dollars 4 to
Dollars 27 5/8 after the company revealed sharply lower net income and
revenues.
US Surgical was Dollars 1 5/8 higher at Dollars 31 1/4.
</TEXT>
