<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Strong close as base rate optimism
reappears - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Good news on inflation in the US brought a dramatic turnaround in the UK
securities markets yesterday, with the stock market replacing an early loss
of 24 points on the FT-SE scale with a gain of similar proportions as the
two week trading account closed. Government bonds gained more than half a
point, the shorter dates edging higher as interest rate optimism revived.
But there was little recovery for shares in Sainsbury, Britain's
premium-rated food retailer, which fell by more than 10 per cent in the
heaviest turnover for two years following a trading statement from the
boardroom.
Food retailing and manufacturing stocks were hit by Sainsbury's statement,
which also deepened the market's doubts over the progress of the recovery in
the UK. The Footsie dipped to the 3,403 area, but dealers were relieved to
see this potentially testing level hold secure. Securities markets made
little response to news of Britain's non-EU trade deficit of Pounds 675m in
December. Although this was above expectations, the market remained
uninterested in the trade deficit.
There was no genuine rally in London until the announcement that US Gross
Domestic Product had risen by an annualised 5.9 per cent in the 1993 fourth
quarter, while the fixed weight price deflator had gained only 1.3 per cent
 -barely half the gain feared by some analysts.
Markets interpreted this as a sign that, with the US economy expanding
strongly while inflation remains subdued, the Federal Reserve was now less
likely to raise US interest rates. UK gilts followed sharp gains in Federal
bonds, and share prices quickly turned higher as increased volume levels
showed themselves on the trading screens in the City's dealing rooms.
At the close, the FT-SE Index stood at 3,447.4, a net gain on the day of
20.1 points. The recovery was spurred by further buying as the stock market
moved into its new trading account. Over the two week account, the Footsie
has risen by around 1.4 per cent, but gains were sharply cut back this week,
when the Index lost 36.8 as some gloomy reports from the retailing sector
undermined the confidence shown over Christmas.
Yesterday's abrupt recovery was slow to spread across the full range of the
market, however. The FT-SE Mid 250 Index, still plagued by fears that more
expiries of individually structured options contracts are pending, closed
down 10.6 at 4,065.8.
Renewed optimism for an early cut in UK base rates brought strong rises in
bank shares and helped some of the retail stocks which had suffered earlier
in the week. Building stocks turned higher as attention focused on next
week's meeting of the Bundesbank policy council.
But the implications of Sainsbury's statement lay heavily across the brewery
and food-related sectors, where nervousness over profit margins has been
unsettling investors for some months.
Trading volume increased as the market recovered, and number of shares
traded through the Seaq electronic network reached 1.14bn. On Thursday,
972.5m shares traded through Seaq for a retail worth of Pounds 2bn, well
above the daily average for the past year. Traders admitted that the
consumer sectors were likely to remain overshadowed by this week's mixed set
of trading results from leading companies but believed that confidence had
improved across the wider range of the stock market.
</TEXT>
