<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A squeeze brought a sharp advance in Footsie futures on the last day of the
equity account, writes Joel Kibazo.
Dealers attributed the early weakness in the March contract on the FT-SE 100
to 'squaring of the books' and the contract fell to its low of 3,413 within
the first hour of trading.
A slow and tentative rally soon prised the big institutions from the
sidelines and that demand turned into a squeeze sending March further ahead.
The release of favourable figures on US inflation not only brought another
bout of hectic demand but also helped bring a turnaround in the fortunes of
the underlying cash market. At the day's peak the contract showed a premium
of 20 points to cash.
It finished at 3,466, around 11 points ahead of its fair value premium to
cash of about 7 points with volume at 16,304.
Volume in the traded options improved to 54,074 of which 16,918 was dealt in
the FT-SE 100 option.
</TEXT>
