<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 94 / Brazil tax defeat jolts stabilisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's economic stabilisation programme has been cast into doubt by the
government's failure to win support for a tax increase required to help
balance this year's budget, reports Angus Foster in Sao Paulo.
A balanced budget is needed for an economic stabilisation programme launched
by Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, finance minister, to tackle inflation of
about 40 per cent a month. The proposed tax increase was relatively small,
and the money can probably be found elsewhere, but the failure has damaged
the credibility of the programme and its architect.
The defeat stemmed from the government's inability to muster a quorum in
Congress on Thursday night, in effect the deadline for several measures to
be adopted this year. The planned tax increase and other measures will now
lapse, costing the government the equivalent of about Dollars 500m (Pounds
334m) in annual revenue.
If Mr Cardoso can present a balanced budget, he plans to introduce a new
inflation index which could gradually become a new currency linked to the US
dollar or a basket of currencies.
To try and balance the budget, the government is likely next month to start
negotiating alternative measures. It may propose a reduction in export
incentives and further cuts in development programmes. Also, public
servants' income tax may go to the federal government rather than to the
states.
</TEXT>
