<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 94 / Zhirinovsky map carves up Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the Russian nationalist, has carved out a vision of
Europe that resembles the continent's brutal reshaping early in the second
world war.
Mr Zhirinovsky drew a map for a retired Swedish ambassador, Mr Rolf Gauffin,
who came to see him in Moscow and subsequently passed it to Le Monde, which
published the map yesterday.
As the newspaper commented, Mr Zhirinovsky's doodlings cannot be entirely
dismissed as 'the imaginings of a crank' because of his success in winning a
quarter of the vote in Russia's elections.
In Mr Zhirinovsky's vision, Russia would regain the Baltic states, except
for the Estonian capital of Tallinn and the inter-war Lithuanian capital of
Kaunas, which would become little city-states.
Germany would repeat its 1938 and 1939 acquisitions of Austria and the Czech
lands, annex bits of western Poland and regain the city of Konigsberg
(today's Russian enclave of Kaliningrad), while Russia would get some of
eastern Poland. Mr Zhirinovsky would take Lvov from Ukraine and return it to
Poland, which lost it as a result of the 1945 Yalta conference. Mr
Zhirinovsky's Russia would take Slovakia.
Further south, Hungary would take Transylvania from Romania, while a greater
Bulgaria would include chunks of Greece, the European part of Turkey and the
ex-Yugoslav republic of Macedonia. Bosnia would be carved up between Serbs
and Croats.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
