<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (30): Faith and
charity overcome 'guilt' - Serious riches / Elizabeth Breton saw her
inheritance as family money, rather than her own, and knew that it needed to
be managed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Greed is good' epitomised the attitude towards making money of a whole
generation of young City dealers. 'Rich is responsible' would more aptly
describe Elizabeth Breton's way of thinking. A landowner and philanthropist,
investment runs in her veins.
Her maternal grandfather, William Mackenzie, a stockbroker, was one of the
founders of the Dundee Stock Exchange. He was also the architect of the
Alliance Trust, the investment trust which today is one of the UK's largest.
The Alliance Trust was formed in 1888 through a series of amalgamations of
Scottish and American mortgage companies. Dundee had always had strong
business connections with the US, but in the 1870s when Americans found it
difficult to pay for goods with cash, Scottish merchants took mortgages over
land in the US as security for goods they sold.
The high interest rates available in parts of the US attracted Scottish
entrepreneurs into establishing trust companies to invest directly in
mortgages.
To lessen risk, the entrepreneurs held firmly to the importance of
diversification, spreading their risks geographically and across a variety
of crops and types of land. This diversification was a guiding principle of
the investment trust movement.
The Dundee Mortgage and Trust Investment company and the Oregan and
Washington Trust company were among those which joined forces to become the
Alliance Trust. Mackenzie, who had been secretary of the Oregan &amp; Washington
Trust, in due course became managing director of Alliance trust.
'My mother was very proud of him; I am proud that the company is still run
from the same offices in Dundee and that he made his money honestly,' says
Mrs Breton, who has a substantial holding in the investment trust company
which her grandfather played an instrumental role in founding.
Her father's family were Lincolnshire farmers, and although he left a
700-acre farm, the principal inheritance was from grandfather Mackenzie. 'I
did not regard the money as my own - I was fairly socialist in those days,
and felt guilty about inherited wealth.'
When her husband was invalided out of the Royal Air Force in 1955, the two
formed a farming partnership and bought 500 acres of arable land in
Gloucestershire; a further 300 acres was added in 1964. Mrs Breton also ran
a holiday cottage business to make use of the unoccupied cottages on the
land.
'Since 1978, I have been involved in a lot of wheeling and dealing. We were
keen to expand into a second farm, and one was bought in Suffolk, financed
by a sale-and-leaseback of part of the home farm. When Suffolk proved too
far away, we relocated to Sussex. In 1987, most of the home farm was sold,
followed by various barns, cottages and land, to maximise assets, with a
view to relocating on better-quality land.'
Land and houses account for almost 40 per cent of her wealth. Because Mrs
Breton wants to buy more farm land, some 35 per cent of her liquid assets
are in the building society. Apart from a tax-exempt special savings account
(Tessa), National Savings products and life assurance, the rest is invested
in the stock market.
'I have always thought of money as something you must be careful with, and,
because I regarded my inheritance as family money and not mine, I felt
responsible for looking after it. In the early 1960s, I realised that my
investments needed to be managed.'
She has relied on the advice of her accountant, Gerry Camamile, and Brian
Tora of Greig Middleton, the City stockbrokers. Tora has managed her stock
market portfolio for the past 20 years on a discretionary basis. He first
took it over after the 1974 stock market crash, until when it had been
invested predominantly in smaller companies, and switched the emphasis to
large blue chips.
The portfolio is still dominated by large companies, with a smattering of
smaller companies. The exposure to overseas markets is obtained through
Fidelity European and the large holding in the Alliance Trust. This is 55
per cent invested in the UK, 25 per cent in North America, 9 per cent in
Europe and 7 per cent in the Far East (nearly all outside Japan), with cash
making up the balance.
Each year, Pounds 6,000 of her Alliance Trust holding is transferred into a
general personal equity plan, to roll up free of income and capital gains
tax. Another Pounds 3,000 is put into a single-company Pep managed by Greig
Middleton, so that the full annual Pep allowance is used up.
Despite her wealth, Mrs Breton lives in a modest stone house in a small
village in Gloucestershire. 'My mother was very much against any kind of
ostentation; she was also very generous.'
One room of the house has been converted into an office, with fax machine
and secretary. Apart from dealing with the paperwork for the farming and
cottage rental business, Mrs Breton uses it to administer her charitable
trust and to deal with other charity work. She discovered 'a firm faith in
Christianity' in the 1960s, and gives away about 10 to 12 per cent of her
income, mainly to Christian organisations. 'I found being a Christian fun;
it also helped me stop feeling guilty about money and to thank God for it.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
