<PROFILE>_AN-EA1CHAHLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (28): A record year,
but will it change our habits? - Unit trusts / A period of low interest
rates might attract savers away from the safety of building societies
towards the greater returns of collective funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unit trusts had their best year ever in 1993. Net sales (gross sales minus
repurchases) were Pounds 8.2bn in the 11 months to the end of December, well
ahead of the previous record established in 1987. Funds under management
edged close to Pounds 90bn, writes Philip Coggan.
Low interest rates were undoubtedly the prime reason for the surge. With
base rates at 6 per cent for much of the year, the income return from
equities (especially when held in the form of a personal equity plan) was
not behind that from deposits. Indeed, many trusts were able to offer
returns well ahead of the building society alternative.
Institutional, as well as private, investors were switching funds from cash
to bonds and equities. The result was an excellent year for share prices - a
fact which reinforced the desire of private investors to buy unit trusts.
Fund managers can hardly believe their luck. Until November 1992, five-year
performance figures were battered by the effects of the stock market crash
of October 1987. At the end of November 1993, the average unit trust had
produced growth of 72 per cent over five years, impressive enough figures to
tempt most private investors.
There is a 'promised land' within sight of the unit trust industry. A long
period of low interest rates might cause a historic shift in British savings
habits; away from the safety (but low returns) available from the building
society and towards the greater returns (but greater risks) of collective
funds. This shift has long since taken place in the US, where the savings &amp;
loans industry (the equivalent of the building society movement) has a
tarnished image.
What investors should demand is an industry which tailors its products to
their needs. One of the most popular types of collective fund in the US is
the low-charging bond fund, which gives investors a safe but steady income.
In the UK, bond funds have never been popular, partly because their high
charges make them look like a poor deal, partly because inflation has eroded
the value of fixed-rate investments.
The only way this circle can be squared is for a major financial name, such
as a high street bank, to launch a low-charging bond fund.
For the fund manager, the only way such funds can work is to attract large
volumes of money - a 0.5 per cent annual charge on a Pounds 1bn fund
represents Pounds 50m a year. It will be interesting to see if a manager
takes up the challenge in 1994.
M&amp;G offers a 'pay as you leave' Pep
One encouraging industry trend is a change in the charging structure. M&amp;G
became the latest group to replace the initial charge on its personal equity
plan with exit charges. This switch, which applies only to the Managed
Income Pep, is designed to reward long-term investors; the exit fee, 4.5 per
cent in the first year, falls to nothing after five years.
Since Peps are supposed to be a long-term investment, this has to be a good
deal for shrewd investors; although M&amp;G's annual fee, at 1.5 per cent,
remains rather high. Over the long run, a higher-than-average annual fee
will drag down the return to the investor.
Fidelity was the first group to introduce Pep exit fees, in 1992. Its
initial charge is 2 per cent; the industry norm is 5-6 per cent.
High-risk funds fare best in a slowly rising market
Hypo Foreign &amp; Colonial's Higher Income Plan must be one of the most
successful unit trust launches ever recorded. The fund, which offered a 10
per cent income (tax-free if held in a personal equity plan) uses a complex
strategy involving the sale of call options to generate the income it
offers.
Investors evidently did not worry too much about the detail - with the
return on their building society deposits falling rapidly, they were only
too eager to grasp any product which offered a double-digit return.
Morgan Grenfell eventually followed Hypo F&amp;C's lead and launched a similar
product in October. But in December, Save &amp; Prosper raised doubts about the
safety of such funds when it cancelled the launch of a trust that would have
been run on similar lines. S&amp;P said that its models showed a significant
risk of capital decline.
Investors schooled in the principle of 'greater reward involves greater
risk' should not be too surprised by this. Any fund which yields several
percentage points above both base rates and gilts must either involve some
risk (of capital loss), or be exploiting some anomaly (which will quickly
disappear in an efficient financial market).
In a statement made after S&amp;P had shelved its launch, Hypo F&amp;C and Morgan
Grenfell said: 'These funds should not be confused with guaranteed funds;
the two funds are actively managed according to market conditions. Neither
the income, nor the level of capital, is guaranteed.'
Broadly speaking, these funds will do best in a static, or slowly rising,
stock market. In a fast-rising market, the funds will underperform their
rivals, since, by selling options on their shares, the funds are giving up
capital gain. And in a falling stock market, the funds will lose money
(although they do have protection against a dramatic drop) and the income
they receive from their call options might also dip.
GT European balanced fund aims for 4.25% yield
The quirks of the personal equity plan rules are giving a boost to the
balanced-fund sector. Balanced funds offer a mix of bonds and equities,
enabling them to provide a higher yield, and (in theory at least) a more
stable performance than a pure-equity fund.
Most balanced funds are UK-based. But GT launched a European Equity and Bond
Fund in November, offering a 4.25 per cent gross yield. Nick Train, GT's
investment director, argues that real interest rates (ie rates adjusted for
inflation) still have plenty of scope to fall in Europe. When they do, money
will move out of cash and into equities and bonds, giving a further boost to
the prices of both asset classes.
Furthermore, Train believes that European shares look cheap, relative to
other major markets, on a price-to-assets and a price-to-cashflow basis.
Since more than 50 per cent of the trust's portfolio will be in European
Union shares, the fund will easily qualify for Pep status. The minimum
investment is Pounds 1,000. The initial charge is 5 per cent (4 per cent on
the Pep) and the annual charge is 1 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>M and G Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
