<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (27): If the
next-to-the-worst should happen - Financing the Family / Critical illness
insurance / An illness does not have to be terminal to trigger a claim, or
even prevent your working. And the lump sum can be spent as you wish
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fear of premature death is being replaced by fear of serious illness as a
marketing tool for the life insurance industry. Medical advances mean that
the chance of a family's main wage earner dying before retirement are now
considerably lower than the chance of contracting a serious,
life-threatening but ultimately non-fatal illness.
But a serious illness can still have a devastating impact on a family's
financial situation, and the consequences for a single person can be just as
harsh. A person may never be able to work again after a stroke or heart
attack, or may not be able to return to the same well-paid career. Serious
illness can also put extra strain on what money is coming in, as nursing
care or home alterations may be needed. Life insurance, which pays out only
on death, is useless in such cases.
So recent years have seen the gradual rise of critical illness, or dread
disease, insurance - policies which pay a lump sum if the insured person
contracts one of a list of common serious illnesses, principally heart
attack, stroke, and cancer. It also covers kidney failure, organ transplant,
heart bypass surgery, and total permanent disability. Some insurers also add
other, more obscure, illnesses to the list, but heart attacks, strokes and
cancer account for by far the largest proportion of claims. The one dreaded
disease excluded by virtually all insurers is Aids, or any HIV-related
condition. General Accident is a notable exception to this.
An illness does not have to be terminal to trigger a claim, or even prevent
you from working; and the lump sum can be spent as you wish: to pay for
treatment, clear debts, buy a more manageable home, or take a holiday to
recuperate. Or, if it seems that you may not return to work for some time,
if at all, the money can be invested to provide an income.
Critical illness insurance was first developed in South Africa, and was
introduced in the UK by Cannon Lincoln in the mid-1980s. Most large insurers
now offer policies, and a few smaller companies specialise in it. So far,
sales figures for critical illness insurance have been low, largely because
of lack of understanding by both the public and financial advisers of what
it is and why it is useful.
Another problem which may have been hindering the development of the market
was solved last year. The National Federation of Independent Financial
Advisers (Nfifa) consulted the insurance industry and medical professionals,
and came up with a list of standard definitions of the seven core conditions
covered by critical illness policies. This should put a stop to anomalies,
such as one company paying out for single heart bypass surgery while another
only covers double bypasses. Some companies have already adopted these
definitions, and more are expected to follow. Previously, financial advisers
were wary of critical illness, because they found it difficult to compare
cover offered by different policies.
Insurers are also trying a different tack, and packaging critical illness
together with other products rather than as stand-alone cover. One example
of this is the proliferation of mortgage endowment policies with critical
illness cover as an optional extra. Critical illness can be relatively cheap
as a mortgage add-on, with extra premiums as low as Pounds 5 a month for
young, healthy people with a good family medical history.
Critical illness cover is also frequently packaged together with life
assurance, either term cover or whole-of-life. Such policies pay out either
when you suffer a critical illness or when you die.
Some more innovative critical illness products can be confusing to buy, as
they are parcelled up with long-term care, medical and permanent health
insurance in addition to life cover. The logic behind this is sensible - a
single policy to provide protection for most of life's unpleasant surprises
 -but it can make it difficult to work out what you are paying for and
whether it is good value. Others have a mix-and-match approach, where you
can choose which benefits you want, but it is difficult for most people to
assess whether they are more likely to get a critical illness, or a
long-term incapacitating condition needing nursing home care.
Some insurers have added a terminal illness benefit to standard life
assurance, which means that the sum insured can be paid out as soon as the
insured person is diagnosed as having only a short time to live. This is
much cheaper than critical illness benefit, but it is much more restrictive:
only a small proportion of critical illness claims are from people who have
received a terminal diagnosis.
Permanent health insurance is another related product: it provides a
replacement income if you are unable to work due to health problems. It can
cover non-life-threatening conditions, such as chronic back problems, as
well as serious illnesses, and pays out weekly or monthly benefits rather
than a lump sum. Payments stop as soon as you recuperate, or return to work.
PHI is particularly useful for the self-employed, who are not covered by
company sick pay schemes, but more people are expected to become interested
in it as the government's reforms of the state sick pay system take effect.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6331 Fire, Marine, and Casualty Insurance.
    P6311 Life Insurance.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT941-12637</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EA1CHAHJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (26): Longevity is
raising new obstacles to inheritance - Financing the Family / Care of the
elderly / Assets over Pounds 8,000 are used to pay for care if a person
enters a residential home by arrangement with a local authority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Longevity is putting a strain on many families. Middle-aged couples can find
themselves worrying about two sets of ageing parents, who may slide rapidly
from active self-reliance to total dependency. Some people in their 60s and
70s are still caring for frail parents in their 80s or 90s, writes Bethan
Hutton.
Anyone in this position comes under not only emotional but also financial
pressure: help with caring at home is not cheap, and full-time care in a
nursing home can cost more than the national average wage.
There is still a common assumption that, when people become too frail or
disabled to look after themselves, a whole range of social services opens up
to help. To a certain extent, that is true - if your local social services
department agrees that there is a need, and if you have no means to pay for
yourself.
But the welfare state no longer automatically pays for long-term nursing
care for the elderly. Since April, any elderly person going into a nursing,
or residential, home by the arrangement of a local authority has to be
means-tested; and any assets over Pounds 8,000 are used to pay for care.
This can include the family home, if no spouse or dependent relative is
occupying it.
Local authorities have no power to force the sale of a home, but they can
put a charge on the property and claim some or all of the proceeds when it
is eventually sold.
The means-testing can also include a person's entire occupational pension,
even if he or she has a spouse who is also dependent on it for an income.
With nursing home fees running at Pounds 400 a week or more in some areas,
it does not take long to wipe out the value of a house or a pension. Only
when assets fall below Pounds 8,000 will the state step in.
Families depend on their local authority to assess that the elderly person
needs care - what is an intolerable situation from a carer's point of view
may be seen differently by the social services department, particularly at a
time of year when the budget is already overstretched. In such cases, if the
family feels it can no longer cope, it will have to find the money for
nursing care privately.
Many old people intend their children to inherit the assets, including the
family home, which they have accumulated over the years. The state pays no
attention to such wishes. Transferring ownership of a property or
investments before a person needs to go into a home may be in vain - the law
says that, if a person has deliberately deprived himself of assets to
increase his entitlement to benefits, he will be assessed as if he still had
those assets.
A lot of people remain unaware of the expense and the regulations involved
in caring for a dependent elderly person until they are themselves landed
with the responsibility, or a relative or friend is in that position. At
that stage, they may begin to wonder whether any provision can be made to
prevent them from becoming a burden on their own relatives or the state.
The good news is that provision can be made, but the inevitable bad news is
that it can be very expensive if you leave it until your late 50s or 60s,
which is when the possible effect of old age and infirmity on a family and
its finances tends to penetrate people's awareness.
A handful of insurance companies offer products designed to meet the cost of
nursing home care. As the population ages, and the welfare state is reduced
to a safety net for those who have not made provision for themselves,
further developments are likely in the next few years.
Existing products come into two main categories: point-of-need products,
designed for elderly people in imminent need of care; and long-term
insurance, which is designed for younger people, worried that they may have
to go into a home at some point in the future.
Point-of-need products are generally based on impaired life annuities, for
which a lump sum (perhaps from the sale of a home or a maturing investment)
is needed. Anyone whose health has deteriorated to the stage where they need
to go into a home is likely to have a reduced life expectancy, so insurance
companies are willing to pay them a higher income from a lump sum than a
healthy person of the same age. Sometimes an agreement is made between the
insurance company and the care provider, that fees will go up by a fixed
percentage each year, or follow the retail prices index, so that pay-outs
can be stepped up in line, avoiding any shortfall due to inflation.
Insurance against possible future need is offered by Commercial Union, PPP
Lifetime, and Prime Health, among others. You pay a small regular or large
one-off premium to buy cover for a certain amount a year or a week. If you
already have a good pension, you may only need to insure for a top-up
amount, rather than the full nursing home fees. Couples can choose joint
life policies.
Payment is triggered when a doctor certifies that you have become incapable
of a certain number of 'activities of daily living', such as eating and
going to the toilet unaided. Some policies have a half-way trigger, so that
a portion of the sum insured can be paid when you become partially
incapacitated, but can still remain in your own home.
The third option is to step up your rate of general savings or pension
contributions, to provide an extra cushion against health care costs;
though, of course, this could reduce your entitlement to benefits, and if
you need care for an extended period, your money could run out.
It is sensible to get independent financial advice before picking any of
these products, as structures and prices vary considerably. The suitability
of any of them will depend on your age, state of health, and current
financial position.
</TEXT>
