<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (23): Debt may be
inevitable but watch the interest - Financing the Family / Going to
university / The cheapest loans, after free overdrafts, are from the state
student scheme - but avoid credit cards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Parents will have to pay less towards their children's university education
from the start of the next academic year, as the government steps up its
programme for shifting the burden of student maintenance away from grants
and parental contributions, and towards more state loans.
But there may still be many parents who are unwilling to see their offspring
start adult life with large debts to pay off, and who prefer to make more
than the contribution required by the state.
Maximum grants for the current academic year are: Pounds 2,845 for students
in London; Pounds 2,265 elsewhere; and Pounds 1,795 for students living with
their parents during term-time. Students can currently borrow between Pounds
470 and Pounds 940 a year from the state Student Loans Company, depending on
where they are studying and whether it is the final year of their course.
Changes announced in the November Budget mean that, from this autumn,
student grants (and therefore mandatory parental contributions) will be cut
by 10 per cent, and the maximum student loan increased to compensate for
this and for the effect of inflation. This means that maximum loans will
increase to between Pounds 915 and Pounds 1,375, or Pounds 670 and Pounds
1,005 for final-year students.
If you are already organising savings for school fees, the cost of three
years' university education can be worked into the equation relatively
easily. However, even parents whose children have used the state education
system up until A-level have no choice about whether to pay when it comes to
university. Grants are means-tested on parental earnings, and anyone with
residual income of more than about Pounds 14,000 has to contribute.
The message from financial advisers is that it is never too early to start
saving for both school and university expenses. Suggestions include personal
equity plans (Peps), building society accounts, tax-exempt special savings
accounts (Tessas), National Savings, unit and investment trusts, and
endowment policies. The combination you choose will depend on: how far in
advance you are planning, your tax position, your attitude to risk, what
savings you have already, and whether lump sums are available to invest or
you are saving out of income.
An independent financial adviser should be able to help work out an
appropriate programme; but be wary of commission-based advisers and tied
agents, who may be tempted to push you towards endowments, which are very
profitable to sell but may not be the most suitable for your needs.
One threat for the future is that some universities, as they see their
government funding gradually reduced, may have to introduce top-up tuition
fees, payable by students or their parents. When the government raised the
possibility of means-tested tuition fees in the mid-1980s, there was a
middle-class revolt, and the idea was dropped, but it has recently returned
to favour in some circles. University vice-chancellors have so far failed to
agree on the issue of fees, but proposals for a number of schemes are under
consideration. Cautious parents, who have sons and daughters due to leave
school in a few years' time, might want to put a little extra aside, just in
case.
If you are about to become a student, you will have a lot to think about and
organise. One of the most important things is to set up a bank account. All
the big high street banks offer special deals for students, involving
incentives such as gift vouchers or cash gifts; but more important are free
banking and interest-free overdrafts.
Debt is now an almost unavoidable part of student life, but some forms of
borrowing are more expensive than others. The most expensive is credit-card
debt - credit card issuers make no special allowances for students, and
charge them the same exorbitant interest rates as everyone else, though some
may waive the annual fee. Credit cards are probably best avoided, unless you
use them strictly for travel and emergencies, and pay off the balance every
month. Unauthorised overdrafts can be almost as expensive: if you think you
are about to go over your agreed limit, tell the bank immediately, and it is
unlikely to penalise you as heavily.
The second cheapest way to borrow, after free overdrafts, is through the
state student loan scheme. Interest is pegged to the rate of inflation (1.2
per cent this year), and repayment does not start until the April after you
graduate. If your earnings are low, repayment can be deferred. The amount
you will be able to borrow will rise steeply over the next few years, and by
1996, loans should account for half of the average student's income. Until
now, a large minority of students have not taken out a student loan, but
this is likely to change as other sources of funding are reduced.
Even students who take out the maximum loan can still suffer a financial
shortfall, particularly if they study in areas with high rents, as they are
no longer eligible for housing benefit. The government does provide some
emergency money, known as access funds, to be distributed by universities to
students facing hardship, but there is rarely enough to go round all the
applicants.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6141 Personal Credit Institutions.
    P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6162 Mortgage Bankers and Correspondents.
    P6282 Investment Advice.
    P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
</IN>
