<PROFILE>_AN-EA1CHAHCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (19): Repayment
mortgages are back - What's new?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In recent years, repayment mortgages have become almost unmentionable among
lenders. They preferred to promote mortgages backed by endowment policies,
and which promised at once the prospect of a return in excess of the loan to
the borrower and fat commission to the lender.
But the virtues of repayment mortgages are beginning to become a selling
point, now that bonus cuts by insurance companies have raised doubts about
whether endowment policies will in future produce enough money to pay off
the loans that they back.
The Australian-owned Yorkshire Bank, operating beyond the bounds of its
eponymous county, is the latest institution to suggest that homebuyers may
be able to make substantial savings by using a repayment mortgage and
increasing payments each year to shorten the term.
For example, Yorkshire Bank says that someone borrowing Pounds 30,000 via
its flexible-payment mortgage, and increasing the initial monthly payment of
Pounds 186.76 by 1.5 per cent a year, would pay off the loan in 17 years 9
months, instead of the standard 25 years.
Assuming the bank's current variable mortgage rate of 7.65 per cent on the
flexible payment mortgage (APR 8 per cent), the borrower would repay a total
of Pounds 56,662, or Pounds 11,753 less than by repaying over 25 years.
On the same basis, a borrower of Pounds 50,000 would repay a total of Pounds
94,273 over 17 years 9 months: Pounds 19,597 less than over 25 years.
Yorkshire Bank charges an arrangement fee of Pounds 150 on the flexible
payment mortgage, which must be repaid by the borrower's 65th birthday. This
means borrowers will have to be under 40, because the bank wants them to be
able to switch back to the 25-year term if increasing payments to reduce the
term become too onerous.
The bank also sets the minimum loan in terms of the monthly payment that a
borrower would have had to make on a 25-year mortgage. There is no upper
limit, though the bank uses its normal criterion of three times main salary,
plus any secondary salary.
There are no penalties or fees for early redemption, in part or in full.
Repayments can be made weekly, fortnightly or monthly, and interest is
calculated daily. Borrowers select the level of payment the intend to make
each year.
UCB Home Loans Corporation, based in Sutton, Surrey, has just launched the
Term Master repayment mortgage, allowing borrowers the choice of monthly
repayment, which can be altered at will on payment of Pounds 25 for each
change.
Higher payments reduce the term. For example, a borrower paying Pounds 327 a
month towards a Pounds 50,000 Term Master mortgage would repay the loan in
25 years, assuming UCB's current variable rate of 7.49 per cent (APR 7.8 per
cent).
A Pounds 34 increase in the monthly payment would cut the term by five
years, saving about Pounds 14,000 on the total cost of the mortgage.
UCB has an administration fee of Pounds 200, and charges a penalty of one
month's interest if borrowers redeem the mortgage before the full term last
arranged.
Foreign &amp; Colonial, the investment trust group, this week launched a pension
plan to be invested in its flagship Pounds 1.6bn F&amp;C Investment Trust.
The F&amp;C pension savings plan will be available either as a personal pension
or as an additional voluntary contributions (AVC) plan, with minimum
contributions of Pounds 5,000 as a lump sum, Pounds 1,000 a year or Pounds
100 per month.
Charges on the plan are to be fixed at an initial Pounds 100, plus a renewal
charge of Pounds 50 a year and a fund management charge of 0.5 per cent.
As investors in the F&amp;C Investment Trust, pension plan holders will have
full shareholders' rights to vote and attend the annual general meeting,
which will also give them an opportunity to question the trust's fund
managers.
After some months of negotiation with the Inland Revenue, Provident Life
will next week launch a flexible annuity portfolio, which will allow people
to retire but leave most of their accumulated pension fund invested, instead
of having to buy an annuity immediately.
Customers transferring at least Pounds 150,000 to the flexible annuity
portfolio from either occupational schemes or personal pensions, including
Section 32 buy-out policies, will receive a minimum payment of Pounds 7,500
a year.
They will have the option of converting to a guaranteed annuity at any time,
but conversion is automatic if the fund falls below the Pounds 7,500
minimum.
Negotiations with the Revenue focused on whether the annual payments could
correctly be defined as an annuity - Provident Life said they could, as
current law describes an annuity as a source of pension payments.
Customers can invest either in Provident Life's own funds or in a range of
other investments of their choice.
Provident Life says the portfolio is much more flexible than other phased
retirement arrangements on the market, noting that it will allow customers
to remain invested beyond the age of 75 instead of being compelled to buy a
final annuity at that point.
Commission is not loaded into the product but is negotiable.
</TEXT>
