<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (15): Placing trust
in the directors - The portfolio, having disposed of two of its holdings
since the last Review, buys units in a fund that monitors who is buying
shares in their own company. It also responds to a reader's suggestion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GOLDSTEIN-JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is 10.45 am, and the post has still not arrived. I do not live in a
remote village, but less than two miles from the local delivery office.
What explanation is there for such a late service in January? I am informed
that the delay is due to 'all the junk mail. . . I wish they would stagger
their deliveries'.
Always on the lookout for investment opportunities, I contemplate searching
out and investing in companies that benefit from the ever-increasing amount
of unsolicited mail.
I mention that, in 'normal times', the post is always considerably later
than that for a neighbouring road, and that the delivery route seems
unnecessarily circuitous. Could he kindly look at the routings again?
The spokesman says he doesn't have the money or the manpower to do this, and
that the Royal Mail suffers from 'government restraints'.
Various excuses for an appalling service have also been given since I
started complaining in March 1987, when the Royal Mail said 'the slippage of
delivery times' was due to 'the unprecedented increase in mail over the past
12 months'; while in 1989 it was because of 'difficulties in retention and
recruitment of staff due to a general shrinkage in the labour market in the
south of England'.
However, this year's complaint seems to have achieved immediate results.
Within a week, the post arrived much earlier - but how long will it last?
What has any of this to do with the portfolio? It demonstrates the
importance of management action in securing the future of companies having
to operate in a competitive environment, and the need to take into account
the effects of government actions.
These considerations have all been borne in mind in producing this
portfolio. I am particularly interested in companies with strong management
and the capability of responding quickly to changing conditions and
customers' needs.
Allied Colloids (speciality chemicals) and EIS (engineering) have
demonstrated their ability to compete worldwide in the face of tough
competition. However, the portfolio will maintain its earlier stop-loss
levels of 205-210p and 365-370p respectively for these companies.
Stop-loss levels are useful for locking in profits and/or preventing large
losses. Unfortunately, when Norcros slipped to its stop-loss level of 170p,
soon after the publication of the last Review, this did not generate the
maximum profit for the portfolio, as the shares subsequently rebounded to
higher levels.
The 170p stop-loss level had been chosen, because I thought Norcros' share
price had been buoyed by takeover hopes, and these had now faded. Expecting
a general market downturn, I feared that any fall in the share price could
be quite steep. But the portfolio did make a modest profit as it had bought
the shares for 158p each.
Burlington Group fell to its stop-loss level of 20p in late November. The
shares had originally been acquired for 11.5p each in October, 1992, but
half the portfolio's holding had been sold for 27p a share in March last
year. This shows the volatility of shares in certain small companies. At 20p
a share, Burlington's market capitalisation is only Pounds 2.96m. It would
make an ideal 'shell' into which an entrepreneur could inject further
activities and rapidly expand the company.
My personal pension scheme has been buying and selling Burlington shares
since 1989, in the hope of a takeover bid, and still retains a modest
holding. If Burlington's shares fell to 16-17p, the portfolio would consider
using its surplus cash to reinvest in the company.
Thus, since the last Review, the portfolio has disposed of two of its
holdings. I had intended the proceeds to be used to buy shares in Renishaw
(a manufacturer of precision metrology and inspection equipment), OIS
International Inspection, or Meggitt, an engineering company. Sadly, the
share prices of these strongly-managed companies did not fall to my expected
buying levels, and so the portfolio was stuck with cash during a period of
low interest rates.
I still like all three companies, and, if the portfolio ever had any spare
cash, would consider buying shares in them if they fell as a result of a
general market downturn to 220-230p for Renishaw, around 80p for Meggitt and
60-65p for OIS.
Perhaps one of the best ways of making sure that a company performs is for
its management to have a large share stake. Although I have recently cooled
towards Pentland Group, its executive chairman, Stephen Rubin, has a massive
shareholding in the company. Its recent acquisition of a 90 per cent
interest in Ellesse, an upmarket sportswear company, should fit in well with
Pentland's other brands, such as Speedo swimwear and Pony shoes.
The portfolio will maintain its stop-loss level for Pentland at 80-85p. My
personal pension scheme has a holding in Pentland and in another of the
portfolio's holdings: William Ransom. I still believe Ransom is attractive,
it has sound management and its chairman has a large shareholding. The
portfolio stop-loss will be changed to 45-47p.
The importance of directors' shareholdings in companies is emphasised by
Pointon York's BRI Director Dealings unit trust. Launched at 100p per unit
in October last year, the trust aims to monitor closely share transactions
by directors in their own companies. The trust emphasises that it does not
blindly follow directors, but applies 'fundamental research techniques' to
try to ensure that any investment by the trust is as a result of following
directors who buy shares because they believe their company has significant
potential rather than the director buying mainly in an attempt to help prop
up the share price. The portfolio will 'buy' 2,500 units in this trust.
A reader of my column in the Weekend FT wrote to me in October, pointing out
that Alvis was a company that appeared to him to have been overlooked by the
market and was well worth mentioning: it not only had excellent products,
but takeover attractions, as Brierley Investments had a 29 per cent share
stake. The value of Alvis's shareholding in Avimo of Singapore was perhaps
worth as much as Alvis's own market capitalisation.
I did some further research and liked what I saw, so my personal pension
fund took a very modest stake in the company on Christmas Eve. The portfolio
will acquire 6,250 shares in Alvis at 40p per share. A stop-loss level of
30-32p will be set, as I feel this could be more of a speculation than some
of the other holdings in the portfolio.
The shares have traded in the 17-48p range since January last year. Despite
defence cuts, there seems to be no end to terrorist activities and civil
wars in various countries, and so Alvis's light armoured fighting vehicles
and robotic bomb disposal equipment still ought to find markets. Through
Avimo, Alvis has considerable interests in non-defence activities, including
providing chemical treatment processes for metal components used in computer
disk drives.
As can be seen from the chart, the portfolio has so far managed to
outperform the FT All-Share Index. But past performance is no guarantee of
future success, and I feel the market could be due for at least a minor
shake-out in the not too distant future. At least setting stop-loss levels
limits the downside.
The author of this feature, which first appeared in the autumn 1991 issue of
the Review, is familiar to many readers as the writer of the Diary of a
Private Investor column in the Weekend FT. The Review invited him to suggest
a Pounds 10,000 portfolio for capital growth, without being too speculative.
The opinions expressed are his own.
