<PROFILE>_AN-EA1CHAG6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (14): Asia Pacific
may not be able to defy gravity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
What goes up must come down. An increasing number of investors are becoming
aware of the fact that Asian markets, many of which hit record highs last
year, may not be able to defy the forces of gravity, writes Emiko Terazono,
in Tokyo.
The case for investing in emerging markets in Asia has been demonstrated by
the rapid economic growth of the south-east Asian region and China, and
increasing liquidity due to low interest rates and capital inflows from
overseas investors.
But, as markets such as Manila rose 151 per cent and Hong Kong 118 per cent
last year, cautiousness over the increased speculation in the markets has
started to prevail.
The boost during the last quarter of 1993 was provided by foreign fund
managers, especially from the US and Japan. Baring Securities estimates that
last year, a total of Dollars 38bn flowed into emerging markets in the
Pacific Rim and Latin America - double the figure for 1992. It predicts that
Dollars 45bn will flow to such markets this year, but sees US investors
switching towards Latin America.
The bottoming out of interest rates in the US points to similar
circumstances in many south-east Asian countries, where rates move in tandem
with the US. Investors may want to bet on further growth potential in the
region, but they will need to keep in mind the fact that the risk of a
correction looms.
Many analysts are downbeat on Malaysia, which, in terms of valuation, has
become the most expensive market in Asia, excluding Japan. However,
political developments may help to support stock prices, as the government
is likely to try and maintain an active stock market if it chooses to hold
an early election.
Investors in the Hong Kong market will need to weigh the risks of an
overheating Chinese economy and an expected wave of capital inflows from the
west and Japan. Meanwhile, the attractiveness of Manila will depend upon
whether the electricity porducers can solve the power crisis, and whether
the economy can post a firm recovery.
Thailand, which rose 90 per cent last year, may be threatened with a rise in
inflationary pressures in the near term. While the economy remains strong,
with firm business confidence and consumption, the central bank has warned
that it will impose a tougher monetary policy this year in order to control
overheated inflation. This could potentially hurt liquidity flows.
An increasing number of investors are starting to focus on laggard markets
in the region, namely Japan and South Korea. Expectations of economic
recovery in Japan, which underperformed, relative to Asia, last year, have
started to attract an inflow of overseas funds. A weakening yen will also
help corporate profits, along with fiscal stimulus and a substantial cut in
income tax.
South Korea has increased its competitiveness as a result of last year's
spurt in the yen, and share prices are expected to be supported by continued
economic growth.
The Taiwan market, which gained 74 per cent last year, currently stands at
about a third of its peak in 1990, and is also favoured due to expectations
of lower interest rates.
So where ought investors to be looking to place funds in Asia?
'On a risk reward basis, it's Japan,' says Mr Geoffrey Barker, at Baring
Securities, in Tokyo. He believes that the risks of investing in Japan are
limited, relative to other Asian markets. Although the rewards may not be
substantial, with the upside of the Nikkei index which is currently hovering
around the 18,000 level, at 20,000, prospects for a crash are slim .
Another reason for moving out of south-east Asian stocks may be the active
purchases of those markets by Japanese investment trusts seen during the
last quarter. . . 'Buying by Japanese individuals may point to the top of
the market,' says Mr Peter Tasker, at Kleinwort Benson, in Tokyo, referring
to a similar phenomenon just before the Tokyo market crashed in early 1990.
The Chinese rediscover their postal heritage: why the Far East is suddenly
attractive to stamp collectors - Page 16
</TEXT>
