<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (13): Wall Street is
sanguine despite prospect of rise in interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US stock markets not only ended 1993 on a firm note, but also opened the
new year in an equally upbeat mood. In the final week of last year, share
prices set a series of record closing highs, and that upward momentum
spilled into the first week of 1994, when the Dow Jones Industrial Average
closed above 3,800 for the first time ever.
Investors hoped that the strong early start to the year would prove a herald
of things to come. The consensus on Wall Street is that the stock market
should do well in the first quarter of 1994. The bullish factors supporting
stocks will be: a further improvement in corporate earnings; strengthening
economic growth; and low inflation. Also, the market should be untroubled by
an interest-rate hike from the Federal Reserve, which is more likely to come
later in the year.
If the forecasts are anywhere near on target, the first quarter should bring
better gains than investors achieved in the final quarter of 1993. In that
period, the Dow rose 5.6 per cent during the three months, to end the
quarter and the year at 3,754.09. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 fared less well,
gaining only 1.7 per cent to 466.45, while the Nasdaq composite index firmed
1.9 per cent to 776.80.
The outperformance of the Dow during the quarter was evidence that investors
were favouring stocks that would benefit most from the accelerating pace of
economic activity - the so-called 'cyclical' stocks such as transportation
companies, paper manufacturers and carmakers. This strategy made sense,
because throughout the last three months of 1993 government statistics
consistently pointed to a rapidly improving economic climate.
While the cyclicals prospered, other sectors languished. Interest-sensitive
stocks, such as utilities, banks and securities houses, which did so well
earlier in 1993, were hit by the jump in bond-market rates. The rise in
long-term Treasury yield, which climbed from under 6 per cent to 6.4 per
cent during the quarter, stopped the broader market from matching the gains
achieved by the Dow.
The final quarter of 1993 also saw national and international politics
affect market sentiment. Concern that the North American Free Trade
Agreement might be blocked by Congress unsettled stocks briefly, before
President Clinton's last-minute lobbying effort brought home a victory.
Overseas events, notably the uprising at the Russian parliament, which
President Boris Yeltsin quashed in early October, the success of far-right
extremists in the December Russian elections, and disturbing developments in
North Korea, also kept traders and investors on their toes.
On the corporate front improved quarterly company earnings, and the
continued revival in the mergers and acquisitions business (in particular,
the prolonged bid battle for control of Paramount Communications and the
acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc by Bell Atlantic) lifted sentiment.
Both situations lured speculators to the media and telecommunications
sectors, where prices surged in anticipation of more bid activity, and
raised hopes that a buoyant M&amp;A market would support share prices in the
first quarter of 1994 and beyond.
In Canada, the dominant themes of the quarter were the general election  -
which turfed out the Conservatives and replaced them with the Liberals, but
which had little ultimate impact on investor sentiment - declining interest
rates, and the still-modest economic recovery. The result was solid gains in
share prices, with the Toronto Stock Exchange composite index climbing 8.2
per cent to end at 4,321.43.
In Mexico, the big story was Nafta. Optimism about the positive impact the
market hoped the treaty would have on the Mexican economy, combined with the
success of the government's fight against inflation, the continued huge
flows of foreign investment into the country, and investors' approval of the
ruling party's nomination of Luis Colosio as its presidential candidate, all
helped the Prices and Quotations Index post a 41 per cent increase during
the quarter to 2,602.63.
</TEXT>
