<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (11): London's
worries re-emerge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sun shone on the London stock market in the final quarter of 1993, and a
successful year was rounded off by a spectacular burst of strength over the
Christmas period.
In terms of total return, the FT-SE 100 Share Index, London's favoured
yardstick, returned 13.3 per cent for the quarter, making 25.2 per cent for
the year.
Relative weakness in Japan and the US was significant, because UK equities
benefited from inflows of international investment cash. US mutual funds, in
particular, saw London as an attractive investment target.
London's advance can be ascribed clearly to growing confidence that an era
of low domestic inflation and interest rates has begun. Economic recovery,
although somewhat hesitant, is perceived to have taken hold, taking the UK
to 'a more advanced stage in the economic cycle than the continental
European economies,' as NatWest Securities, the investment arm of the UK
bank, has it.
A moment of doubt was suffered in the market towards the end of November,
when some analysts feared that the new chancellor might raise taxes and thus
threaten economic recovery.
Such fears proved premature. Tax rises have, in effect, been put off until
the spring, when Social Security, VAT and mortgage tax adjustments will
revive the market's old fears. Just ahead of the Budget, the stock market
was also granted its base-rate cut, whereupon it immediately began to
discount the next one.
The outlook for the this year remains optimistic, although the exceptionally
vigorous December performance has brought a cautious reaction. On the
economic front, prospects are not greatly different from last year. And
there are no serious political worries, because the government has plenty of
time in which to recover its standing in the opinion polls.
The driving force for the London market has been the huge outflow of US
investment funds, which had already reached about Dollars 75bn by the end of
the third quarter. Much of this went into European, but also Pacific Rim,
markets. London benefited, both directly (from its share of the US funds)
and indirectly (because the City is the financial channel through which many
international fund flows reach continental European markets).
These US outflows could well fall, or change direction, this year, if only
because both Wall Street and Tokyo are likely to improve their relative
performances. Also, London was briefly upset before Christmas by fears that
the Federal Reserve might be obliged to push US interest rates up to curb
the economic rebound.
The possibility of higher, rather than lower, rates has already begun to
trouble the UK. While conventional long-dated UK government bonds returned
34.4 per cent last year, index-linked gilts gave a return of 20.6 per cent,
indicating that not all the fears of inflation have been laid to rest.
This combination - uneasiness over inflationary pressures, and doubts about
whether last year's cash inflows can be repeated - lies behind analysts'
predictions for this year. Most expect further progress in the short term,
with a further cut in base rates providing the encouragement.
Valuations on UK equities continue to discount a great deal of optimim for
economic recovery. The optimists would remind us that 'Bull markets climb a
wall of worry', but others would prefer to see the next round of corporate
results. Confidence in the depth of the recovery in the UK economy has still
to be fully justified, and any doubts could bring a correction in share
prices.
</TEXT>
