<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (9): No nasty late
surprises - Year-end tax planning / A November Budget leaves time for
thought. And investment decisions should not be based on tax-saving alone,
lest you lose more than you save
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For the first time, investors can plan their end-of-tax-year finances
without the fear that last-minute surprises will pop out of the chancellor's
budget briefcase.
These were unleashed in November, and investors will have had plenty of time
to digest the effects by the end of the tax year.
However, John Cole, at Berry Birch and Noble, independent financial
advisers, warns against leaving action until the last minute: 'The mad
scramble to make financial decisions at the end of the tax year is to be
avoided. Better to plan ahead and make decisions at a more leisurely pace
during the year.'
It is also worth remembering that no tax-planning measure should be based
solely on the amount of tax which might be saved. If the underlying
investment is not sound, investors will lose much more than any potential
tax saving. The main areas are:
Income tax
Those who are happily married should make use of all personal allowances,
and transfer assets to the lower-rate taxpayer to avoid paying higher-rate
tax on them. James Higgins, of fee-based adviser Chamberlain de Broe, says:
'This is particularly important for older couples, where age allowance can
be reduced or lost by having too much income arising in the wrong name. For
example, people should watch out for maturing guaranteed income bonds.'
The married couple's allowance is automatically allocated to the husband.
Tax relief will be restricted to only 20 per cent in the 1994-95 tax year,
instead of up to 40 per cent, so there is no longer any point in
transferring the whole allowance to the wife unless the husband is a
non-taxpayer. An election for a transfer or split must be made before the
end of this tax year for 1994-95.
Frank Akers-Douglas, of chartered accountant BDO Binder Hamlyn, reminds
parents that their children each have a personal allowance of Pounds 3,445
for the current tax year, and advises parents to use them up; for example,
through distributions from non-parental discretionary trusts.
Non-taxpayers with building society accounts should register before the end
of the tax year in order to receive the whole of next tax year's building
society interest gross.
Capital gains tax
Everyone has a CGT allowance of Pounds 5,800 in the current tax year. The
abolition of indexation to increase or create losses from Budget day will
have deprived many investors of the ability to reduce their CGT bill, while
others will face a bill which they might otherwise have escaped.
However, those who would like to reinvest gains in an unquoted trading
company can roll over their CGT liability by doing so. Otherwise, investors
should try to 'bed-and-breakfast' shares by selling them one day and buying
them back the next, to use up their annual exemption. There are costs
involved - broker's commission and stamp duty - so it is important to
calculate whether these outweigh the benefits. Crystallising gains by
selling and buying back shares will reduce a future CGT bill, because a
higher base will have been established.
Cole says: 'As an alternative to bed-and-breakfasting, many people are now
bed-and-pepping - selling shares and repurchasing within the tax-free
environment of a personal equity plan on a self-select basis.' This is only
suitable for those who have not already used up their annual Pep allowance
(see Investments, below).
Akers-Douglas advises against selling an asset with a large gain near the
end of the tax year. By deferring the sale until after April 5, the tax will
be delayed for a further 12 months.
Since CGT is payable at an investor's marginal rate, Cole suggests creating
gains in a spouse's name, if the spouse is in the lower-rate tax band, by
transferring the assets to them first.
Inheritance tax
IHT is not payable on the first Pounds 150,000 of someone's estate when they
die. An individual can limit their estate to this figure by giving away
their wealth, but such gifts will be 'potentially exempt transfers' unless
the donor survives for seven years.
However, annual gifts of up to Pounds 3,000 are not dependent on this time
restriction. The relief can be carried forward for one year only, so a
married couple could collectively give away Pounds 12,000 without any IHT
liability.
In addition, someone can make limitless small gifts of up to Pounds 250 (but
not more than Pounds 250 to any single individual).
Value Added Tax
Fuel bills will increase from April 1, when VAT at 8 per cent is imposed,
but the tax can be avoided by buying the year's domestic fuel in advance.
This is because VAT is charged at the rate that applies at the date of
invoice or payment, whichever is earlier.
Pensions
Pensions are highly tax-efficient, since premiums are grossed up and are
invested in a tax-free fund. However, benefits cannot be drawn until
retirement.
Those with a personal pension can use 'carry back' provisions, allowing them
to mop up unused tax relief from any of the last six tax years, which is
particularly useful for self-employed people with fluctuating annual
earnings.
'If someone wants to reduce his or her 1992-93 income tax bill, a
contribution must be made before April 5,' said Higgins. 'The investor then
has until July 5 before making the election to carry back. Some people
confuse these two dates - the payment must actually be made before the year
end for it to be carried back to the previous year.'
Those in a company pension scheme, who are eligible to a top up, can do so
with additional voluntary contributions. Unused reliefs cannot be swept up
in later years, so the maximum contribution into an AVC must be made by the
end of this tax year.
Investments
A personal equity plan allows investors to hold shares, investment or unit
trusts investing in UK and other EC equities, free of income tax and CGT.
The investment limits are Pounds 6,000 a tax year into a general Pep, and
another Pounds 3,000 into a single-company Pep. Those wanting to invest the
maximum must do so before the end of the tax year, but charges on a Pep tend
to make them most worthwhile only to a higher-rate taxpayer.
The Business Expansion Scheme, which allowed full income and CGT relief on
an annual investment of Pounds 40,000, has been replaced by the less
generous Enterprise Investment Scheme. This gives tax relief of 20 per cent
on a maximum investment of Pounds 100,000 in a qualifying trading company.
The final legislation will not be in place until the Finance Bill receives
royal assent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
