<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (5): Tax deferred
may be tax saved - Investing offshore, roll-up funds / The chief reason for
using such funds is the expectation that you will one day be in a lower
income tax bracket - say, on retirement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOANNA SLAUGHTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Offshore roll-up funds may have lost some of their investor appeal in
today's low-interest-rate environment, but they remain valuable financial
planning tools for those who want to accumulate income and to defer their
tax liability.
Roll-up funds provide investors with exactly the benefit that their name
suggests. Income and capital gains are retained and rolled-up within the
fund. Investors are only liable to tax when they withdraw their money.
The funds offer a number of investment benefits and tax-planning
opportunities, therefore, and, unlike some offshore investment vehicles,
they have clear advantages for UK, as well as overseas, investors.
Roll-up funds are invariably based in favourable tax environments, so
investors enjoy the gross accumulation of interest and dividends, and money
that would be lost to tax each year in a UK account continues to earn
interest, giving a further investment boost.
But the most significant planning benefit is investors' ability to defer the
payment of tax. Nick Smith, marketing director of Guinness Flight, says:
'The main reason why roll-up funds are still of interest to UK investors is
that they can basically decide at what point they want to be taxed.'
Graham Barker, executive director of Fidelity Investments, agrees: 'The
whole benefit occurs because you can choose when to make the realisation,
and therefore when to pay the tax. And you can avoid tax completely if you
are by then non-resident or go to work abroad. So investors have nothing to
lose, and everything to gain.'
Jeremy Norfolk, managing director of Cater Allen, which plans to launch a
roll-up fund later this year, adds: 'The other related advantage is that you
can effectively take the same income out of a roll-up fund by selling
shares, but you only pay income tax on the capital gain made by the shares.'
David Major, personal finance partner of the accountancy firm Touche Ross,
'uses roll-up funds a lot for people who do a considerable amount of work
overseas. After enjoying a gross roll up, they can redeem the funds when
they are not resident in the UK for tax purposes.'
Certainly, the chief reason for placing money in a roll-up fund is the
expectation that the investor will be liable to lower rates of income tax at
some future date. Obvious candidates for the funds, therefore, are those who
are currently higher-rate taxpayers but who reckon that their tax position
will change when they retire, either because they will have less income, or
because they anticipate retiring abroad and will thus escape any UK tax
bill.
UK employees who know that their career may take them abroad at some time
can also make good use of a roll-up fund. If they withdraw cash when
overseas, they will not be liable for UK tax. Conversely, temporary
residents or workers in the UK can put money offshore in a roll-up fund
until they move elsewhere.
Roll-up funds also provide financial planning opportunities within the
family. For example, parents are normally liable to tax on any income
arising from money that they have given to their under-age unmarried
children. But if this cash is kept in a roll-up fund until the child is 18,
the accumulated interest can then be set against the child's own personal
allowance. Similarly, a roll-up fund can be used to mop up the personal tax
allowance of a non-working or low-income spouse.
Elsewhere, roll-up funds can be a useful aid for UK companies (or for the
self-employed), if they want to defer tax on investment income. Barker
comments: 'If a family business plans to relocate or expand in two years
time, and it knows that it will then make a trading loss, that will be the
year to redeem the roll-up fund investment.'
Most roll-up funds are cash-based, but there are some equity and bond funds.
For instance, the Guinness Flight International Accumulation Fund is a
roll-up umbrella vehicle with five bond funds and two equity funds among its
sub funds.
Donald Elkin, a director of financial adviser Wilfred T. Fry, says there are
a number of circumstances where equity-based roll-up funds are helpful:
'There is no taxable event until you make a realisation; so if you are only
resident in the UK for a couple of years, you could shelter your equity
investments in a roll-up. Conversely, if you were going to Hong Kong, say,
in two years time, and you wanted to make an equity investment, you could
anticipate your departure.'
Most UK investors use roll-up funds that invest either in a single currency
or in a managed currency vehicle, however. Richard Roberts, marketing
manager of Barclays International Funds, comments: 'Single currency funds
are one step removed from deposit accounts, and the main driving force is
the interest rate. Managed currency funds are a further step up the risk
spectrum, because returns are dependent on the manager's skill.'
The deferral of tax is not the only reason for investing in a roll-up
currency fund, as Graham Barker points out: 'There are two major uses for
roll-up funds - currency management and tax planning. If you want to pay the
bills on a holiday home in Spain, I defy anyone to find a better way to do
it than through a money fund. You escape the banks' commission and
electronic charging fees. Transfers at Fidelity are at unbeatable rates of
exchange, and we cover 23 separate currencies.'
Enthusiasm for roll-up funds has been muted of late, however. John Stephens,
investment director of Hill Samuel Jersey, says: 'The problem is that, with
interest rates so low, the returns are pretty meagre. The tax tail can start
to wag the dog when interest rates are at these levels.'
One suspects, too, that modest investors remain wary about placing money
offshore, and nervous of the Inland Revenue's future intentions. The answer
to the first worry is to stick to a household name. The pedigree of many of
the financial institutions that offer roll-up funds is impeccable. Touche
Ross's David Major says: 'It is a very competitive market. We are looking at
all the major players.'
For example, Rothschild Asset Management has Pounds 1.3bn invested in its
two Guernsey-based money funds. The major part is invested in its roll-up
vehicle, the Old Court International Reserves fund.
Most managers also feel that roll-up funds have ceased to be an Inland
Revenue target, as the two glaring loopholes have already been closed. It is
no longer possible to convert income into capital gains for tax purposes or
to switch within an umbrella fund without triggering a chargeable event.
'There is no word that the Inland Revenue is looking at roll-up funds,' says
Major. 'While you could say that a deferred tax is a saved tax, in strict
terms there is no Revenue loss.'
Happily, the Revenue appears to agree. Roll-up funds were not touched in the
November Budget.
</TEXT>
