<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (2): Safer than it
used to be - Investing offshore, introduction / The Budget made one helpful
tax change, but most Britons do not see the point of going offshore. On this
page and the next three, we consider some of the possibilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK is still perceived as a reluctant member of the European Union, and
the field of offshore investment is no exception.
European efforts to encourage funds to be sold across national borders, via
the Ucits (undertaking for collective investment in transferable securities)
are making only slow progress. According to Robert Fleming, while 4,500
Ucits funds have been authorised, fewer than 250 are registered in more than
one country.
Whereas, there are some signs of cross-border shifts - the amount of German
money managed by mutual funds in Luxembourg is now larger than that in
Germany itself - the UK has been particularly recalcitrant. According to
Steen Steincke, managing director (retail) for Robert Fleming Europe: 'Very
few foreign groups have tried to cross-sell into the UK from European bases,
and those that have tried have had limited success. Why is this? Perhaps
because the UK is a relatively mature, very competitive market-place with
high levels of compliance supervision. These factors make entry costs very
high.'
Nor, given their peculiar structure (involving three sets of published
prices), is there much sign of UK funds being sold overseas. 'Although most
UK unit trusts have actually registered as Ucits funds, they remain as
virtually domestic market products' says Steincke.
Perhaps the most important factor dissuading Britons from investing offshore
is that, for most people, the advantages are far from clear. If it is tax
efficiency you want, you can invest Pounds 9,000 in personal equity plans
each year (Pounds 18,000 for a married couple), and receive all income and
capital gains tax-free. Only a limited number of people have sums greater
than that to throw around.
But Kenneth Clarke's Budget did make one tax change that could give offshore
funds an advantage. The Inland Revenue decided to close a loophole which
would have allowed cash unit trusts to deduct tax at 20 per cent, giving
them an advantage over building societies, which take off tax at 25 per
cent.
However, the Revenue decided that all unit trusts would henceforth pay tax
at 25 per cent. According to the Association of Unit Trusts and Investment
Funds (Autif), these proposals would mean that 'foreign dividends received
by UK trusts will be taxed at 25 per cent, while the credit for the tax paid
will be restricted to 20 per cent. If basic-rate taxpayers invest direct in
overseas equities, or though an offshore fund, they will only pay tax at 20
per cent.'
Thus, there will be a 5 per cent tax saving for basic-rate taxpayers
investing offshore. It seems likely that this loophole will be exploited
most by non-Pep qualifying funds, such as those investing in the US.
Another recent initiative might also change matters. Charles Schwab, the US
discount broker, has launched a version of its 'no-load' service. Investors
can buy a range of funds without any initial charge, a saving of up to 5-6
per cent.
For the moment, the service is limited to just three fund management groups:
Guinness Flight, Wright Investor Services and Rothschild Asset Management.
Furthermore, the only Rothschild funds available are its currency funds,
which bear no initial charge in any case.
However, if the Schwab service expanded to include a large number of funds,
it might represent an attractive alternative to onshore funds for
cost-conscious investors.
The tax advantages of investing offshore have traditionally applied more to
bond and deposit funds. Offshore bond funds, unlike their onshore
counterparts, can pay income gross. This can make them attractive to
non-taxpayers, who otherwise would have to wait to reclaim the tax on an
onshore fund from the Inland Revenue. However, taxpayers should note that
they are obliged to declare the income received from an offshore fund to the
Revenue.
Deposit funds offer the chance to 'roll-up' interest gross. While this does
not avoid tax, this system has two tax advantages. The first is simple:
money compounded gross grows faster than money compounded net. The second
advantage is that the investor does not have to pay the tax bill until the
money is withdrawn; if, for example, he or she is about to retire and move
into a lower tax bracket, this may have advantages. However, there is one
important caveat: with taxes rising, there is a chance investors may end up
paying an even higher tax bill.
The Budget will have reinforced the offshore advantages of these funds.
According to Autif: 'Dividends received from cash or bond funds situated in
Luxembourg or Dublin will be taxed at only 20 per cent in the hands of UK
basic-rate investors, who will (therefore) be encouraged to invest in
interest-invested offshore funds.'
A more simple advantage of investing offshore is that building societies
sometimes offer higher rates to offshore customers, because their costs are
lower overseas.
What about safety? One name that instantly springs to mind when the word
offshore is mentioned is Barlow Clowes. The memories of such scandals may
prevent some from investing overseas. However, the cautious offshore
investor should be able to sleep at night. There are a number of
well-respected names operating offshore, such as GT and Fidelity, and many
funds are also SIB-recognised, which means that the UK's chief financial
services regulator has accepted that regulation in the offshore centre is
equivalent to that in the UK, and that the funds are run in a proper manner.
Despite the relatively slow progress it has made, the offshore market will
continue to expand. The greatest beneficiaries of offshore investment are
expatriates, who find it advantageous to keep their investment out of the
tax net of both their home and adopted countries. As multinational
corporations increasingly switch their executives from country to country,
and as more people decide to retire to sunnier climes such as France and
Spain, the demand from expatriates seems bound to increase.
</TEXT>
