<DATE>940128
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets: Athens pauses after scaling new peaks -
But opinion remains divided as to the market's next move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After two months of frenzied activity, triggered by the flotation of six
leading Greek construction companies, investors on the Athens stock exchange
are pausing for breath.
The Athens general index relinquished 0.4 per cent yesterday to close at
1,109, its fourth decline in five days.
The index peaked at 1,194 on January 18, its best level for more than two
years, although still well short of the bourse's all-time high of 1,684 set
in July 1990.
Brokers and market analysts attributed the fall to profit-taking by foreign
investors, who drove the market up by some 20 per cent earlier this month,
reflecting the current enthusiasm for emerging markets among US and
international fund managers.
The brokers estimate that institutional investors abroad accounted for at
least 50 per cent of daily turnover, which has averaged more than Dr15bn
(Dollars 60m) since the start of the year. The increased pace of trading is
all the more remarkable given that average daily turnover in 1993 amounted
to just Dr2.5bn.
Yet opinions are divided about the market's next move. With the average p/e
ratio at 20, Greek equities now look expensive, while overall economic
prospects are gloomy.
Greece shows few signs of emerging from recession, with growth for 1994
projected at only 1.2 per cent and the public sector deficit likely to
worsen from last year's 13.9 per cent of gross domestic product.
Mr Phaedon Tamvakakis, managing director of Hambros Hellenic Growth Fund,
said: 'It is really quite hard to justify a continuing rise for the moment.
The fundamentals are not encouraging and Greek equities no longer seem
cheap.' However, Mr Yannia Tegopoulos, chief analyst at Midland Pantelakis
Securities, sounded more sanguine. 'The rise has been based on liquidity
rather than p/e ratios so far, and there is still lots of money around to be
allocated.'
With more than 30 Greek companies in a lengthening queue for listings on the
bourse, there will be plenty of shares available over the next few months.
The success of the construction sector listings, all heavily subscribed, has
brought new entrants flocking to the market.
The construction companies, all family-owned, were seeking funds to finance
new equipment purchases and provide working capital as they prepare to bid
for more than Dr6,000bn worth of infrastructure projects being co-financed
by the European Union.
Their example is being followed by other growth-oriented companies anxious
to avoid high interest rates, still averaging above 20 per cent for working
capital.
Ms Katerina Ferentinos of BZW Hellas said: 'The market is now set to broaden
considerably, with the arrival of companies from sectors that traditionally
have shunned the stock market in favour of raising financing privately.'
One such applicant is Teletypos, which controls Mega Channel, Greece's most
successful private television station. Owned by a consortium of Greek
newspaper publishers, the company intends to raise Dr10bn, including an
international tranche of about Dr2.5bn.
Two passenger ferry lines, Strintzis and Dane, keen to start rennovating
their fleets ahead of the EU's deregulation of coastal shipping at the end
of the 1990s, will be the first shipping concerns to join the bourse. At the
same time, a number of blue chip companies are planning rights issues.
Michaniki, until November the only big construction company on the bourse,
has announced a Dr9.2bn rights issue. Credit Bank, the largest private bank,
plans a capital increase of close to Dr30bn.
The flow of new issues is likely to continue for much of 1994. Although the
socialist government which came to power last October has radically
curtailed Greece's privatisation programme, it still plans to float 15 to 20
per cent of OTE, the state telecommunications company, on the bourse this
year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
