<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / International Company News: Dow Chemical optimistic as
deficit is cut to Dollars 48m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dow Chemical, the US chemicals group, yesterday reported net losses of
Dollars 48m for its fourth quarter because of heavy provisions for
litigation against Dow Corning, the biggest US manufacturer of breast
implants, in which it holds a 50 per cent stake.
However, the deficit marked a sharp improvement from the net losses of
Dollars 250m in the previous year's fourth quarter, and the figures were
accompanied by an upbeat statement about the outlook from Mr Frank Popoff,
chairman and chief executive.
'While many of the challenges facing us will persist in 1994, we expect
earnings to improve because of the company's on-going efforts to enhance
productivity and as a result of recovering world economies and improved
industry fundamentals,' Mr Popoff said.
Dow has been suffering from poor cyclical demand for its products,
particularly from Europe.
Volume was flat in the fourth quarter, but sales were 5 per cent lower at
Dollars 4.5bn because prices fell.
Fourth-quarter earnings benefited from a Dollars 90m pre-tax gain on
investments, but this was heavily outweighed by a Dollars 192m after-tax
provision for litigation against Dow Corning over leaking implants. The
result translated into losses per share of 18 cents, compared with losses of
92 cents last time.
However, Dow said that excluding both unusual items from the latest figures,
and a Dollars 433m charge against the previous year's fourth-quarter pre-tax
profits, the group would have reported earnings per share of 30 cents,
against 10 cents a share last time.
For the full year, Dow reported a 5 per cent drop in sales to Dollars 18.1bn
because of a 4 per cent fall in prices and a 1 per cent fall in volumes.
Net income was Dollars 637m, compared with net losses of Dollars 496m last
time, and earnings per share were Dollars 2.33, against net losses of
Dollars 1.83. But Dow said that if unusual items were stripped out, earnings
per share would have been flat at Dollars 2.02, compared with Dollars 2.01.
</TEXT>
