<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / International Company News: Sentrachem plans R294m rights
issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW CURTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sentrachem, South Africa's third-largest chemicals producer with yearly
sales of R2.5bn (Dollars 770m), has announced a R294m rights issue to reduce
borrowings and finance local projects.
Mr John Job, managing director, said yesterday the local stock market was
buoyant and Sentrachem needed the money 'in the bag' well before the
country's first non-racial election in April. Otherwise it risked waiting a
long time for suitable market conditions to materialise.
He said the decision to concentrate on upgrading local facilities partly
reflected the collapse of plans to buy Chemplex, the Australian chemicals
group, in 1992 after the Reserve Bank tightened foreign exchange
regulations. Sentrachem was determined to acquire offshore assets and was
making progress with approaches less sensitive to exchange control
constraints.
Sentrachem will issue new shares at 850 cents each, a large discount to the
market price of 975 cents, with some of the cash used to trim long-term
borrowings which stood at R360m at the group's August 1993 year-end. The
group is upgrading facilities and has plans for a citric acid plant and
agricultural chemical feedstock operation, with a combined capital cost of
R150m.
Next year, the group wants to take control of Sanachem, a subsidiary which
exports crop-protection products jointly owned by Farm-Ag, a chemicals
supplier.
</TEXT>
<XX>
