FT  28 JAN 94 / International Company News: Air Canada set for Osaka
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Canadian government is to allow Air Canada to move into the Japanese
market in direct competition with rival Canadian International, while
raising the possibility of new routes later for Canadian.
Air Canada said it would begin flying into the new Kansai airport, Osaka,
when it opens in September. It originally wanted Tokyo, but Narita airport
is saturated.
Both airlines want more Asian destinations, saying too much Asia-Canada
traffic is being taken by US Airlines.
Air Canada said Hong Kong is its first priority, and then new routes to
China.
In Calgary Canadian International said a CDollars 246m (USDollars 187.7m)
equity infusion from American Airlines will be in place this spring, so that
the parent PWA's financial restructuring can go ahead.
