<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / International Company News: Thyssen faces doubts over
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Thyssen, the German steel and engineering group, has reported weak domestic
orders in the first quarter of its 1993-94 fiscal year, raising doubts about
the group's recovery this year.
Total orders in the three months to December 31 1993 fell 5 per cent with
the figure for European Union down 13 per cent. Orders for Thyssen
Industrie, the capital goods division, dropped by 16 per cent, reflecting
mainly poor market conditions in the car industry. The sharpest drop was in
machinery which fell by 38 per cent.
The group did not disclose first quarter financial results, but said
turnover had improved 1.2 per cent over the same period the previous year,
mostly due to foreign subsidiaries. Turnover in Thyssen Stahl, the steel
division, was down 7 per cent and in Thyssen Industrie by 10 per cent.
Steel losses forced Thyssen into the red for the year ended September 30
1993. It returned a DM864m (Dollars 493.7m) loss, after DM348m pre-tax
profits the year before. Without the steel division, the group would have
recorded an operating profit of DM774m, Mr Heinz Kriwet, chief executive,
said. Thyssen will omit a dividend.
</TEXT>
