<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JAN 94 / Burton revives retail worries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The patchy and volatile nature of the recovery in consumer spending was
highlighted yesterday by disappointing sales figures from fashion group
Burton and a lacklustre statement from clothing and food retailer Marks and
Spencer.
The statements contrasted sharply with Wednesday's news from fashion
retailer Next that sales in the half-year to January 31 were expected to be
18 per cent up, and yesterday's announcement from MFI, the furniture group,
that sales since Boxing Day were up 14 per cent. MFI also unveiled a
near-doubling of pro-forma interim profits to Pounds 24.5m.
The figures sent analysts scurrying to rewrite their full-year profits
forecasts, with Burton downgraded from about Pounds 60m to between Pounds
40m and Pounds 45m, and MFI lifted from about Pounds 60m to about Pounds
70m. M&amp;S was unchanged at Pounds 860m-Pounds 880m.
Sir John Hoskyns, Burton's chairman, told the company's annual meeting that
sales for the first 21 weeks of the financial year, to January 22, were no
better than last year.
Sales were 5 per cent up at Debenhams, but down 5 per cent in the multiple
chains - which include names such as Top Shop, Dorothy Perkins and
Principles - reflecting tough competition and increased promotional activity
in clothing. Sir John said the multiples were responding to strategic
changes, 'but change of this kind, which was urgently necessary, is also
painful'.
Lower mark-ups to make prices more competitive, plus markdowns to clear
stock, resulted in a reduction in Burton's gross margin of 1.5 percentage
points, although costs in the period had been reduced by 2 per cent.
M&amp;S said that after a disappointing November, sales had recovered to the
extent that the six weeks to January 1 had met expectations. But it operated
at full price throughout Christmas, and the margin loss in the
post-Christmas sale, in money terms, was the same as last year. With
increased sales, that suggests the overall gross margin for the period will
be higher.
Yesterday's figures added to the mixed picture of Christmas and new year
trading, with disappointing results from Dixons and Kingfisher, solid
performances from the likes of M&amp;S, Sears, Boots and WH Smith, and sharper
improvements from Signet, Laura Ashley, Storehouse, and Next.
'The upturn in spending is far from smooth,' said Mr Tim Kirkwood, analyst
at Panmure Gordon. He said the vast difference in profit expectations
between 'recovery' stocks such as Next and Burton reflected not just
internal factors, but the weakness of the consumer recovery. If recovery was
stronger, he suggested, most retailers would be seeing the benefits.
Lex, Page 18; MFI rise Page 20
</TEXT>
